This is where it gets interesting. A mechanic isn’t valuable because it exists—it’s valuable because it changes what actions become possible.

Think of your mechanics as a cognitive move set, like abilities in a strategy game.

For example, imagine you’re trying to launch Wild Hawg.

Instead of just brainstorming, you deliberately invoke mechanics.

Situation	Mechanic	Action
Stuck	Meta-Wave Reattack	Change abstraction level. Stop designing gummies; design the distribution system instead.
Too many ideas	Comparative Distillation	Find the invariant across successful brands.
Missing information	Tracer Dye	Run a small ad or prototype and observe what propagates.
Overwhelmed	Semantic Zoom	Zoom out to strategy, then back into packaging.
Unsure	Semantic Rangefinder	Estimate how far you are from retail readiness.
Too much work	Leverage Multiplier	Build something reusable instead of one-off.
Lost	State Anchor	Return to the last validated checkpoint.

Notice you’re playing mechanics, not just thinking.

