The endgame

The most powerful use isn’t solving one problem.

It’s building a compiler.

Problem

↓

Identify state

↓

Measure deltas

↓

Select mechanics

↓

Compose pipeline

↓

Execute

↓

Measure new deltas

↓

Learn

↓

Update mechanic library

Every solved problem makes the compiler better.

At that point, you’re no longer collecting ideas. You’re building a meta-system that learns which mechanics work for which kinds of problems and composes them into increasingly effective solution pipelines. The key test is empirical: if the chosen mechanics consistently lead to better outcomes than ad hoc reasoning, the library becomes a genuine advantage rather than just an elegant taxonomy.